"Maud Le Boteler是Edmund Boteler的女儿，于1200年出生在爱尔兰庫迪 維斯特亞斯德盧姆藍尼。她于大约1230年与Sir Thomas Dillon Lord of Drumrany在爱尔兰庫迪 維斯特亞斯德盧姆藍尼结婚。他们至少是4个儿子的父母。她去世于1244年在爱尔兰庫迪 科克科克享年44岁。"},"hr":{"1200–1244":"1200.–1244.","1206–1244":"1206–1244.","1232–Male":"1232.–preminuo","1234–Male":"1234–preminuo","1236–Male":"1236–preminuo","1238–Male":"1238.–preminuo","–Male":"preminuo","1206":"1206","1238":"1238.","1236":"1236","1234":"1234","1200":"1200.","1244":"1244.","1232":"1232.","ABT 1234":"oko 1234.","Abt 1236":"oko 1236.","about 1230":"oko 1230.","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Irska","Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irska",", County Cork, Munster Province, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Irska","Ireland":"Irska","Of Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irska","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irska"},"cs":{"1200–1244":"1200–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1232–Male":"1232–Zesnulý","1234–Male":"1234–Zesnulý","1236–Male":"1236–Zesnulý","1238–Male":"1238–Zesnulý","–Male":"Zesnulý","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1232":"1232","ABT 1234":"okolo 1234","Abt 1236":"okolo 1236","about 1230":"okolo 1230","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Irsko","Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irsko",", County Cork, Munster Province, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko","Of Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irsko","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irsko"},"da":{"1200–1244":"1200–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1232–Male":"1232–Afdød","1234–Male":"1234–Afdød","1236–Male":"1236–Afdød","1238–Male":"1238–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1232":"1232","ABT 1234":"omkring 1234","Abt 1236":"omkring 1236","about 1230":"omkring 1230","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Irland","Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irland",", County Cork, Munster Province, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","Of Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Irland"},"nl":{"1200–1244":"1200–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1232–Male":"1232–Overleden","1234–Male":"1234–Overleden","1236–Male":"1236–Overleden","1238–Male":"1238–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1232":"1232","ABT 1234":"circa 1234","Abt 1236":"circa 1236","about 1230":"circa 1230","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ierland","Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland",", County Cork, Munster Province, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","Of Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland"},"en":{"1200–1244":"1200–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1232–Male":"1232–Deceased","1234–Male":"1234–Deceased","1236–Male":"1236–Deceased","1238–Male":"1238–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1232":"1232","ABT 1234":"about 1234","Abt 1236":"about 1236","about 1230":"about 1230","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ireland","Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland",", County Cork, Munster Province, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","Of Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Le","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Thanh, Hung, Minh, Dung, Tuan, Hai, Hoa, Thuy, Son, Anh, Long, Hoang.  Chinese Hong, Sang, Chi, Dong, Tong, Lai, Hang, Man, Han, Ho, Phoung, Chan.  Korean Tam, Phong, Nam, Thai, Tuong, Chung, Thach, Tinh, Manh, Tham, Uyen, Vang.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 樂, meaning ‘happiness’ in Chinese: from the first element of the personal name Le Fu (樂父), style name of Yan, son of the Duke Dai of Song (ruler of the state of Song, reigned 799–766  BC ). Yan's grandson Le Ju (樂莒) inherited Le (樂) as his surname.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 勒: (i) from the second element of the placename Shu-Le (疏勒), an ancient state (located in present-day Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region) during the Western Han dynasty (206  BC –25  AD ). (ii) a surname near the Bohai Sea region during the Han dynasty (206  BC –220  AD ). (iii) a surname traced back to the Hun ethnic group in northern China during the Jin dynasty (265–420  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Feng, Gang, Wei, Chun, Guo, Jin, Kin, Ping, Yan, Yun, Zhang, Chau, Du, Hau, Hung, My, Sau.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 岳 (or 嶽), meaning ‘high mountain’ in Chinese: traced back to Si Yue (四岳 or 四嶽), said to be the title of an official post in charge of sacrificial rituals on the site of famous mountains during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ) and Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC )."]},{"name":"Lok","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Tat, Wing, Ying Lin, Chi Ming, Ching Wah, Chun, Chung Man, Han, Kam, Kam Tim, Kin.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 樂, see   Le   1.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 陸, 鹿, 逯 and 禄, see   Lu   5 and (7-9)."]},{"name":"Li","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ming, Li, Jian, Hong, Yan, Ping, Jing, Yong, Ying, Hui, Jin, Min, Chung.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 李, meaning ‘plum’: (i) said to have been adopted in place of the Chinese surname 理 (also pronounced Li; meaning ‘rules’ in Chinese) by Li Zhen (利貞), son of an official called Li Zheng (理徵) in the late Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). It is said that Li Zhen's father incurred the displeasure of King Zhou of Shang (died 1046  BC ) and Li Zhen fled to a wasteland area, where he survived on wild plums. After his return to civilization, he changed his surname to Li (李 ‘plum’), a word with the same pronunciation. The original surname, 理, is said to be from Li Guan (理官), the name of a post of officials in charge of legislation in ancient China. Li Er (李耳), also known as Lao Tzu or Lao Zi, traditionally regarded as the founder of Taoism, is believed to have been a descendant of Li Zhen. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chi Li (叱李) family from the Xianbei ethnic group during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) in the early years of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), sixteen high officials with different surnames were granted the surname Li (李), the surname of the royal family of the Tang dynasty, by Emperor Taizong of Tang (died 649  BC ), because of their contributions to the establishment of the Tang regime. (iv) the surname can also be traced back to several minority ethnic groups in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 黎, meaning ‘black’ or ‘multitude’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Li (黎), the name of an ancient state (located in Changzhi in Shanxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ), which was annexed in the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ) and later granted to Fengshu, also known as Li Hou (黎侯, 'Marquis Li'). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Su Li (素黎) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group, during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Boteler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a maker of leather bottles, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bouteille</i> ‘bottle’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Le Boteler was born in 1200, in Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland as the daughter of Edmund Boteler. She married Sir Thomas Dillon Lord of Drumrany about 1230, in Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1244, in Cork, County Cork, Ireland, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1200–1244":"1200–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1206":"1206","